## Why This Is Asked
Tests ability to craft an actionable, scalable incident response for a complex streaming pipeline with multi-tenant QoS, data correctness guarantees, and real-time rollback requirements.

## Key Concepts
- Observability: per-tenant backlog metrics, distributed traces, structured logs
- Backpressure handling: tenant-aware throttling, dynamic rebalancing
- Data correctness: idempotency, exactly-once semantics, DLQ handling
- Rollback safety: canary, traffic shaping, validated resumption

## Code Example
```javascript
// Pseudo-idempotent write with dedupe key
async function process(msg){
  const id = msg.id;
  if(await dedupe.has(id)) return;
  await warehouse.write(msg.payload);
  await dedupe.set(id, true, TTL);
}
```

## Follow-up Questions
- How would you test the roll-forward vs rollback paths?
- Which metrics define success for resuming traffic, and how are tenants verified?

## Why This Is Asked

Tests practical mastery of deduplication in real systems, combining transactional patterns, Kafka exactly-once semantics, and robust auditing.

## Key Concepts

- Exactly-once processing
- Transactional outbox pattern
- Kafka transactions (transactional.id)
- Idempotency keys and dedupe stores
- Compensating actions and audit trails

## Code Example

```javascript
// Pseudo: within a DB transaction
BEGIN;
UPDATE orders SET status='PAID' WHERE id = :orderId;
INSERT INTO outbox (order_id, event_type, payload, created_at) VALUES (:orderId, 'OrderPaid', :payload, NOW());
COMMIT;
```

